        "type": "p",
        "text": "The role of medication in treating social anxiety is a deeply personal decision that should always be made in close consultation with a qualified healthcare professional. For some individuals, medication can be an incredibly effective tool for managing severe, debilitating symptoms and creating a necessary window of opportunity to engage effectively in therapy and implement behavioral changes. Antidepressants, such as SSRIs or SNRIs, are commonly and successfully prescribed for social anxiety. However, medication is not a magic cure-all and is almost always most effective when combined with structured therapy and healthy lifestyle modifications. It is important to carefully weigh the potential benefits and risks of medication and explore all available treatment options."
