        "type": "p",
        "text": "One of the most insidious aspects of social anxiety is avoidance behavior. When a situation causes distress, the natural human instinct is to avoid it at all costs. While this provides temporary relief, it ultimately reinforces the anxiety in the long term. By avoiding social interactions, individuals miss out on crucial opportunities to learn that these situations are not as threatening as they perceive them to be. This creates a shrinking comfort zone, where the person feels safe only in highly controlled environments or in complete isolation. Overcoming avoidance requires gradual exposure to feared situations, a process that can be incredibly challenging but is absolutely essential for long-term recovery and building resilience."
