        "type": "p",
        "text": "The role of self-compassion in overcoming social anxiety cannot be overstated. Often, individuals with social anxiety are their own harshest critics, constantly berating themselves for their perceived flaws and social shortcomings. Self-compassion involves treating oneself with the same kindness, understanding, and forgiveness that one would naturally offer to a close friend. It means acknowledging that everyone makes mistakes, experiences awkward moments, and struggles with insecurities at times. By cultivating self-compassion, individuals can build a stronger sense of self-worth and reduce the debilitating fear of negative evaluation from others, making social interactions feel less like a performance."
